<!--
  Protocol: diagnose-then-fix
  See architecture spec §5.2, §8.2

  Failure recovery protocol. When a workflow step fails:

    1. The Wave Executor (or Workflow Engine) marks the step as faulted and
       captures the error with full context
    2. The Conductor dispatches a Debugger agent with the error context
    3. The Debugger performs root-cause analysis — it does NOT fix anything
    4. The Debugger's diagnosis is handed to the original agent (or a
       replacement agent) for the fix
    5. After the fix, ONLY the faulted step is retried (not the whole wave)
    6. If the retry fails a second time, execution escalates to the user

  Rationale: blind retry wastes context and often re-produces the same
  failure. Root-cause first, then targeted fix.

  This protocol is NOT opt-in per workflow — it triggers automatically on
  any step failure and cannot be disabled.

  Status: stub
-->
<protocol id="diagnose-then-fix" version="0.0.1">
  <status>stub</status>
  <opt-in>false</opt-in>
  <escalation-threshold>2 consecutive retry failures</escalation-threshold>
</protocol>
